T1  - Public inputs and child schooling in Brazil
AU  - Birdsall, Nancy
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 18
IS  - 1
SP  - 67
EP  - 86
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/05/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(85)90007-0
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387885900070
AB  - Household data from a one percent sample of the 1970 Brazilian census are used to analyze the effect of public inputs, i.e., the ‘supply’ of schooling, on children's school attainment in Brazil. The household data are combined with measures of school availability and quality derived directly from the same census data; the measures are based on the income and education of schoolteachers in each of 169 different areas of the country. Elasticities of demand with respect to these public inputs are estimated; these elasticities are high in both rural and urban areas. In urban areas, the positive effect of public inputs is greater for children from households with poorer and less-educated parents. In rural areas, the positive effect of public inputs is greater, if anything, for children from households that are relatively better off, at least compared to other rural households.
