DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(85)90011-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387885900112
AB  - Data from 39 individual nationalized jute weaving mills are examined to establish a typical pattern (at the mill-level) for the productivity of operating capital, namely operating looms. (This pattern also applies in this case to operating labour.) Productivity of operating capital characteristically increases first at a decreasing rate as a function of mill-age, and after peaking declines asymptotically. This relationship is approximated by a quadratic function with exponential fade, and reasons for the typical pattern are suggested. This pattern, which differs from that suggested by conventional theories of productivity progress, may be common for manufacturing plants in LDCs.
